mvc.controllers

Class GamePlayController.PointerMoveAnimation

  • java.lang.Object
    • util.ExtendedAnimationTimer
      • mvc.controllers.GamePlayController.PointerMoveAnimation
  • Enclosing class:
    GamePlayController

    private class GamePlayController.PointerMoveAnimation
extends ExtendedAnimationTimer
    This class implements abstract class ExtendedAnimationTimer. Why I used this class? Firstly, I needed to create animation of game pointer's move. I tried to use TranslateTransition, but I found it bad when you need to switch pointers. And drawing on canvas was the best solution, but I needed to redraw scene every frame.

    • Constructor Detail

      • PointerMoveAnimation

        PointerMoveAnimation(java.lang.String keyText,
                     GamePlayController.StepCause stepCause)
        Constructor is quite complicated. Firstly it sets GamePlayController.movingPointer to true - this says that we're moving pointer. And, secondly this part sets two variables: goalX and goalY.

        Note: if "goal cell" is wall animation will be stopped.

        Parameters:
        keyText - text of pressed key, used for recognizing direction.
        stepCause - says "What caused this step?", and used to recognize "What to do with undo and redo stacks?"

    • Method Detail

      • handle

        public void handle(long now)
        This method is an implementation of ExtendedAnimationTimer.handle(long). Here's all move animation logic:
        1. Changing position of pointer: if goalX is grater than GamePlayController.pointerX - last one increments, otherwise - decrements. Same this with goalY and GamePlayController.pointerY.
        2. Stopping animation: if reached end (pointerX == goalX && pointerY == goalY) - animation stops.

        Starting cell is peculiar (see CellType.START to read how it looks). Firstly, it must be on smaller layer than GP, but higher than lines, that GP leaves. Secondly, to draw triangle on the start in use this scheme:

        1. Using some value in range 0.0 - 100.0 for current point (start - x1)
        2. Mapping this value to range 0.0 - .0
        3. Giving received value to method that draws triangle
        4. Repeating with y1, x2, y2, x3 and y3

        Specified by:
        handle in class ExtendedAnimationTimer
        Parameters:
        now - time in nanoseconds (same as System.nanoTime(), but with some additions)

      • start

        public void start()
        Overrides method ExtendedAnimationTimer.stop() because there're some calls of this method before starting animation. So, uses variable-stopper.
        Overrides:
        start in class ExtendedAnimationTimer

      • stop

        public void stop()
        Overrides method ExtendedAnimationTimer.stop(). Why I have chosen to override? That's because of GamePlayController.movingPointer. This method is called many times, and I don't wanted to type such code: 
        
 movingPointer = false;
 stop();
 // return;
        Overrides:
        stop in class ExtendedAnimationTimer
